SIG SAUER® introduces the SB15 Pistol Stabilizing Brace, a shooter’s aid that is designed to improve the single-handed shooting performance of buffer tube equipped pistols.

This veteran-designed and U.S.-manufactured accessory enhances accuracy and reduces felt recoil when using an AR-style pistol.

Made from high-quality, elasto-polymer, the SB15 is manufactured to close tolerances and fits all pistols equipped with an AR-style buffer tube 1.0” – 1.2” in diameter. A flexible cuff with two adjustable nylon straps allows the SB15 to be custom fit to any user.

title: For Sale:  Flag Scalpers
postcontent: Don't forget to check in a couple of times a day to flag the ripoff ammo scalpers. If it seems like a ridiculous price (like 10cents per round for 22lr), just flag it as overpriced. If nothing else, it annoys the scalpers. Some scalpers claim it's a waste of time, but I think it has some positive effect. If nothing else it just seems like the right thing to do. Immoral ripoff scalpers need help from the Armslist community, to understand that their immoral activity, may technically be legal, but makes the ripoff scalpers as bad as the garbage that sells food and gas for triple the value during emergency situations. Worthless scalpers, please learn some decency. Stop scalping your fellow shooters. Earn a decent, morally upright living, instead of being a low life, dirty, ripoff scalper guy.

title: For Trade:  Weapons cannot be seized from your car during traffic stops
postcontent:
Berkeley County needs a new sheriff. Election TOMORROW, Tuesday June 10
I have brought this up again because it is time for elections in Berkeley County and the Sherirff's office is at stake. Know your rights when it comes to legally storing your weapon in your vehicles according to state law and while carrying/ or not with your valid CWP.
1) State Law prohibits local municipalities from taking your weapon from your vehicle.
"Officer safety" is satisfied when you are standing outside your vehicle or seperated from your weapon. 
2) Officers cannot seize your property unless you are under arrest.
SC code section 23-31-520
This article denies any county, municipality, or political subdivision the power to confiscate a firearm or ammunition unless incident to an arrest. 
3) If you are a CWP holder and your gun is not on your person, you do not have to present your CWP in a traffic stop. This has been mistaught in many CWP classes. If your gun is stored legally in accordance with state then you are not carrying a concealed weapon. This has been corrected my CWP instructor and was verified with the SLED head of CWP program.
4) See MIchigan v. Long, 103 S. Ct. 3469 (1983)
Search the above court ruling to read where they denied the right to search for and seize weapons for "offer safety"unless certain criteria were met. I wasn't even so much as patted down even after presenting a cwp so the officer certainly wasn't afraid as he turned his back on me to enter my vehicle with me directly behind him.
Since I did not pose a threat to the officer and I was not under arrest, he can not enter my truck and confiscate my property. 
To satisfy "Officer Safety" criteria the officer must feel that the person is DANGEROUS and may elude the officer during a stop in order to retrieve a weapon and use it. Typically officers would have "dangerous" people in cuffs and have backup during the stop.
Three lawyers agreed that my civil rights were violated but there was no financial loss substantial enough for them to sue unless I shelled out cash. And honestly, I am not the sueing type. I just don't want bad cops, or bad departments with "unspoken or unwritten policies" patrolling Berkeley County or anywhere else I may roam.
I kept an arrest journal of every contact I had with the officer and his supervisor. It is lengthy and pasted below in the trade section. The supervisors comments are the most shocking, especially when posed a question about entering my house. I have asked for recordings of all of the interactions but was told none of them were recorded.
I contacted Sheriff DeWitt about this and spoke with him twice. I can only assume that his inaction on this matter means 1) he supports the actions taken, 2) made this unspoken policy, or 3) has no control over his department.
This interaction coupled with statements made by DeWitt after Sandy Hook leads me to the conclusion that our Sheirff and his department's philosophy on gun control when dealing with law abiding citizens does not match that of his constituents. 
What do you think? Have you kept up with the frequent mishandling of gun control issues across the country by local municipalities and the militarization of local enforcement agencies with federal monies? We need a pro-2nd (and 4th) ammendment sheriff who will see to it that his deputies operate in accordance with state law and the mandates of the Supreme Court. It is election time. This is an important election at an important time.

FYI-
I have MANY friends in law enforcement and all agree with my position on this. Not one offered an argument in favor of the officer or supervisor especially after learning that 1) the officer did not check me for weapons after presenting a card saying that I have one on my person 2) knowing that I am 235lbs of scary looking redneck and the officer turned his back on me while I hovered over his shoulder 3) The officers unfamiliarity with my SERPA holster leading to him repeatedly (and laughably) yanking on a loaded weapon.
Number one comment from cop buddies(and gun buddies) is officers are not trained on how to operate every firearm system and it is unreasonable to assume that they can all clear every weapon without incident. Many guns can be stored in vehicles and they can all function differently or even malfunction because of miscare by the owner and officers take a risk in handling unknown weapons. 
Ever tried to check a Phoenix HP-22 to see if it is loaded(total pain in the ass)? Ever pulled a slide back and have an unintended discharge due to a broken firing pin? Ever seen a cop mishandle a weapon and shoot himself in the foot (youtube)? Ever seen anyone accidentally shot while standing next to someone who is trained in firearms mishandling a weapon?

This is n't a national issue on Glenn Beck or The Blaze. This is something you can handle right here in your own town. I have heard back from others who have had similiar issues. Pass it on to friends who vote and carry. Post it on your facebook pages. Too many folks like us who just want to live our lives and enjoy our freedoms skip these local elections. I suggest you make this one.

title: For Sale:  Colt Junior Factory Walnut Grips Astra Cub FIE A27 Best Old Stock 1970s Production for .22 Short or .25 ACP Variants
postcontent:
Our # GRCJR

From years of packaged storage in a very old Southern Warehouse come these very attractive and original factory grips for the Colt Junior series pistols, chambered in .22 Short and .25 ACP Caliber. Manufacturer was probably an Italian subcontractor to Colt’s Patent Firearms manufacturing company. Construction is cut checkered dark European Walnut, with Nickel plated brass factory Colt Logo Medallions on each panel. Note that these do NOT come with screws, and we do not have any screws for the Colts they fit. Final distributor, or attempted distributor, was a company known as Bingham Ltd. of Atlanta, and that is whose packaging these grips come in. The distributor received substantial notoriety during the Reagan Era for some of its products. We believe these grips were overruns from Colt’s production of the Junior Pistols that ceased in the early 1970s. They will only fit a Colt Junior Pistol, or one of its ancestors or descendants, chambered in .22 Short or .25 ACP calibers. The pistol should have an external hammer and should have its magazine release located on the left side of the grip frame. Direct ancestor to the Colt Junior was the Astra Cub; and its brief-lived descendant was the FIE model A27 Best. These grips will not fit a Colt 1908 Vest Pocket .25 Pistol. They will not fit an Astra Constable .380 Pistol. They will not fit an FIE E27 pistol. They will not fit the chain handle of a 19th Century Italian Bidet. They will only fit the Colt Junior, and the Astra Cub, and the FIE A27 Best pistols chambered in .22 Short or .25 ACP calibers. This is the first time in 40 some odd years we have run across any of these grips for sale, and our supply of them is limited. We’re offering the set in the photos, or their substantially identical mates from the same batch, each set for only $ 39.00.

Grips, Magazines, Slings, Holsters, Scopes, Mounts, Parts & Most any small light items, entire accessory orders only $10.00 total shipping no matter how many a person buys. $10.00 for an entire order, Not $10.00 per item or anything of the sort. $20 Flat Fee on magazine orders to Alaska, Hawaii, or Puerto Rico, and gun parts to PR civilians must ship to an FFL. Magazines and any small light non-gun items ride free with ammo orders. We accept checks with no more than 7 days hold. title: For Sale/Trade:  Bulgarian Circle 10 Military Makarov.
postcontent:
Made in 1982 as a military sidearm.
Light wear on the barrel, and on the slide.

This is a great gun, but I have 2 guns in 9x18. One was inherited, so I can't sell it. This one will just save me the trouble of registering another gun when I move.
Makarov's have a fixed barrel. So, unlike most other pistols out there, the barrel doesn't move at all. Which makes it inherently more accurate than other pistols its size. I've gone toe to toe against Baby Glocks in 9mm and .40, and came out on top in accuracy. 

9x18 is a bit of a middle ground between .380, and 9mm. And it was used since its development as a military and police round. The Russians still use it, but are only now developing alternatives. 

Comes with authentic leather holster, Red Star grips, black import grips, a shoulder holster, and an ankle holster.

If you're interested, I can provide a mix of 9x18 ammo.

title: For Sale:  (2) Fuel Can Five Gallon NATO Style Brand New Unissued 18x13x6.5" Green with Lever Lock Lid
postcontent:
I am selling (2) brand new, unissued NATO Style five gallon steel fuel cans.

Constructed of lightweight steel with triple handles for easy tie-down. The narrow profile allows multiple cans to be stacked or tied on the bumper of a truck or Humvee. Lever-lock spill-proof lid with rubber gasket. Fuel can measures approximately 18"x13"x6.5" A thick enamel coating on the inside makes this fuel can superior to all other.

Made for years and years of rough use with any fuel, these are the gold standard for current militaries all over the world. Never before have we seen these in brand new, unissued condition and supplies are extremely limited.

Customer Reviews:
Cans arrived in new condition, as advertised. I bought used ones previously when offered and wasn't dissapointed either. These have good paint inside, worth the extra money. Additionally I find them much better than the plastic junk with the akward EPA spill prone nozzles. 

I hate the new CARB compliant cans so much that I bought these. These are the BEST! Brand new, solid, they pour beautifully, seal air tight, and are heavy duty. You cannot go wrong with these. Get them before they are sold out.

These are the best metal gas cans I have ever seen. I have traveled with several of these cans fully loaded with gasoline in the trunk of my compact car. I never once detected the odor of gasoline. I drive with the windows up and the air conditioning on. The sealing lid on these cans is incredibly effective and I easily learned how to open and close the lid with one hand, while pumping gas with the other. Because these are 20 liter cans, you are easily able to put five full gallons of gasoline into the can without having to fight with the EPA nozzles and adapters on the gas pumps. I have a number of these cans and I will be getting more of them soon.

High quality fuel can. This is NOT the cheap Chinese junk. This is the real deal with solid welds, quality coating, and a positive seal. If you purchase one of these I recommend also getting the fuel spout that is made for this can. I got one for each fuel can I purchased and they are just as high quality as the cans.

Selling for $75 for both! I only have (2) left - so, get them fast!
